can be used as follows: "You just moved to Pittsburgh, eh?"%0a%3c %0a%3c End of Questions (Interrogative): "Eh" is also used as a tag here - one important thing to note is that its functionality as a tag in Canadian English differs slightly from that in Standard American English. Namely, "right" cannot be added to yes/no questions in American English; however, "eh" can indeed be added to yes/no questions in Canadian English. For example, this is a perfectly valid sentence: "Did you see the news this morning, eh?"%0a%3c %0a%3c End of Imperative Sentences: "Eh" can also be used at the end of imperatives; however, it is important to note that the level of certainty/authority in the imperative will determine whether the use of "eh" is appropriate. "Eh" is typically only used in imperatives that are more like suggestions or are not forcefully authoritative. For example, "eh" can be used in imperatives as follows: "Stay safe out there, eh!"%0a%3c %0a%3c In the Middle of Sentences (Confirmation): "Eh" here is used as "okay" is sometimes used in Standard American English. It sometimes serves the purpose of seeking confirmation that the listener heard or understands what the speaker said preceding the "eh". For example: "First, you need to turn left, eh, and then take the first exit." %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
